<subSubSection pageId="179" pageNumber="180" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="179" pageNumber="180">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="179" pageNumber="180">
A branched unarmed shrub up to 4 m in height, vegetative parts shortly adpressed pubescent, somewhat glabresent on older parts. Leaves sessile, 2-14 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.5-2.6 cm, narrowly to broadly oblong, dark green, acute to obtuse, entire, base attenuate. Inflorescemce branches from the upper leaf axils forming a terminal, panicle-like inflorescence of branched cymes with primary branches to 7 cm long, the axes densely pubescent; bracteoles 1 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.5 mm, scale-like, caducous, pedicels 2-15 mm; outer sepals 4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2 mm, broadly lanceolate, apiculate, the margin ciliolate; inner sepals 4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
4 mm, mucronate, elliptic or suborbicular, membranous; corolla 1.1-1.5 cm long, white, unlobed, midpetaline bands pilose; anthers exserted; ovary pilose; style pilose, divided c. 3 mm above base; stigmas c. 3 mm. Capsule acute, pilose, 1-seeded; seeds minutely hirsute. [
<bibRefCitation author="Sa'ad, F" journalOrPublisher="Bronder Offset, Rotterdam" pageId="210" pageNumber="211" pagination="1 - 287" refId="B314" refString="Sa'ad, F, 1967. The Convolvulus species of the Canary Isles, the Mediterranean region, and the Near and Middle East. Mededelingen van het Botanisch Museum en Herbarium van de Rijksuniversite Utrecht. Bronder Offset, Rotterdam: 1 - 287" title="The Convolvulus species of the Canary Isles, the Mediterranean region, and the Near and Middle East. Mededelingen van het Botanisch Museum en Herbarium van de Rijksuniversite Utrecht" year="1967">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sa’ad">Sa'ad</normalizedToken>
1967
</bibRefCitation>
: 110; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bramwell, D" journalOrPublisher="Flora of Egypt" pageId="200" pageNumber="201" refId="B60" refString="Bramwell, D, Bramwell, Z, 2001. Wild flowers of the Canary Islands (2nd ed.). Rueda, Madrid, 1-437." title="Wild flowers of the Canary Islands (2 nd ed.). Rueda, Madrid, 1 - 437." year="2001">Bramwell and Bramwell 2001</bibRefCitation>
: 262 (photo); 
<bibRefCitation author="Schoenfelder, P" journalOrPublisher="Kosmos, Stuttgart" pageId="211" pageNumber="212" pagination="1 - 319" refId="B322" refString="Schoenfelder, P, Schoenfelder, I, 1997. Die Kosmos Kanarenflora. Kosmos, Stuttgart: 1 - 319" title="Die Kosmos Kanarenflora" year="1997">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Schönfelder">Schoenfelder</normalizedToken>
and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Schönfelder">Schoenfelder</normalizedToken>
1997
</bibRefCitation>
: 174-175 (photo)]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="179" pageNumber="180" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="179" pageNumber="180">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="179" pageNumber="180">
Endemic to the Canary Islands: Gran Canaria, Tenerife, La Palma, La Gomera, Lanzarote, Fuerteventura (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="179" pageNumber="180">Bourgeau</emphasis>
1426, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="179" pageNumber="180">Asplund</emphasis>
721, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="179" pageNumber="180">Murray</emphasis>
s.n. [30/4/1894]).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="179" pageNumber="180" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="179" pageNumber="180">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="179" pageNumber="180">A very distinctive species because of its shrubby habit and white flowers in a terminal paniculate inflorescence.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
